post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_15248603_15248697_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3196}}, "n3337": {"so_15248603_15248697_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3070}}, "n4659": {"so_15248603_15248697_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3958}}}, "15248603": {"ViewCount": "909", "Body": "<p>When I'm defining some variables like this:</p>\n<pre><code>int a = pop(), b = pop(), c = pop();\n</code></pre>\n<p>does C++ give a guarantee that <code>a</code> is going to be initialized first, then <code>b</code> and then <code>c</code>? or is the order not defined?</p>\n", "Title": "C++: variable declaration initialization order", "CreationDate": "2013-03-06T13:26:58.783", "LastActivityDate": "2013-03-06T13:33:00.480", "CommentCount": "5", "FavoriteCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "15248603", "Score": "14", "OwnerUserId": "9611", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "15248697": {"Id": "15248697", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>[dcl.decl]/3 says</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_15248603_15248697_0\">-3- Each init-declarator in a declaration is analyzed separately as if it was in a declaration by itself.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Which means your code is treated like:</p>\n<pre><code>int a = pop();\nint b = pop();\nint c = pop();\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-03-06T13:30:44.107", "CommentCount": "8", "CreationDate": "2013-03-06T13:30:44.107", "ParentId": "15248603", "Score": "10", "OwnerUserId": "981959"}});